task-AudioMotorLocalizer_bold.json.Instructions: One of five different conditions will be spoken. They are 'hand', 'mouth', 'foot', 'speak', 'saccade', and 'rest'. For the 'hand' condition drum your fingers on the table until the next word is spoken. For the 'foot' condition, wiggle your toes until the next word is spoken. For the 'mouth' condition, move your moth by saying nonsense words such as 'balabalabala' until the next word is spoken. For the 'speak' condition, without vocalizing tell yourself a story in your head such as how you got here today. For the rest condition, do not perform any task. These five conditions will repeat for the 10 minute duration of the task.
task-AudioMotorLocalizer_bold.json.TaskDescription: A motor localizer used to define primary and secondary motor and somatosensory areas, Brocas area. This motor localizer is used for subjects with poor eyesight and can not see the screen. Includes everything in the normal motor localizer except the saccade condition.

task-AuditoryLocalizer_bold.json.Instructions: Passively listen to stimulus, stay still, and try to keep your eyes closed for the duration of the stimulus
task-AuditoryLocalizer_bold.json.TaskDescription: Listen to story auditory localizer. Used to define auditory cortex. The localizer contains short ~15s segments of a babbling brook, a snippet of spoken language from the podcast this american life, and a snippet of music from a arcade fire song. Snippets were repeated for 10 minutes of the stimulus.

task-MotorLocalizer_bold.json.Instructions: A fixation dot will appear in the center of the screen. One of six different conditions will appear on screen they are 'hand', 'mouth', 'foot', 'speak', 'saccade', and 'rest'. For the 'hand' condition drum your fingers on the table for the duration the word is on screen while maintaining fixaiton. For the 'foot' condition, wiggle your toes for the duration the word is on screen while maintaing fixation. For the 'mouth' condition, move your moth by saying nonsense words such as 'balabalabala' for the duration of the word on screen. For the 'speak' condition, without vocalizing tell yourself a story in your head such as how you got here today. For the saccade condition, an array of dots will appear on the screen, saccade around between the dots. For the rest condition, simply maintain fixation on the center point. These six conditions will repeat for the 10 minute duration of the task.
task-MotorLocalizer_bold.json.TaskDescription: A motor localizer used to define primary and secondary motor and somatosensory areas, Brocas area, eye fields, and IPS.

README:
## An fMRI dataset during a passive natural language listening task

This dataset now has a dataset descriptor currently available on biorxiv, that describes all of the data and code available for working with this dataset. It can be found:

LeBel, A. et al. A natural language fMRI dataset for voxelwise encoding models. bioRxiv 2022.09.22.509104 (2022) doi:10.1101/2022.09.22.509104

A(n incomplete) list of papers using this dataset from our group are listed below:

Tang, J., LeBel, A., Jain, S. & Huth, A. G. Semantic reconstruction of continuous language from non-invasive brain recordings. bioRxiv (2022)

LeBel, A., Jain, S. & Huth, A. G. Voxelwise Encoding Models Show That Cerebellar Language Representations Are Highly Conceptual. J. Neurosci. 41, 1034110355 (2021)

Tang, J., LeBel, A. & Huth, A. G. Cortical Representations of Concrete and Abstract Concepts in Language Combine Visual and Linguistic Representations. bioRxiv 2021.05.19.444701 (2021) doi:10.1101/2021.05.19.444701

Jain, S. et al. Interpretable multi-timescale models for predicting fMRI responses to continuous natural speech. Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems 34, (2020)

## Dataset Derivatives

1. preprocessed data: fully preprocessed data as described in previous works.

2. textgrids: aligned transcripts of the stimulus with start and end point for each word and phoneme. 

3. pycortex-db: hand-corrected surfaces for each subject to be used in visualization. This is best used with the pycortex software. 

4. subject_xfms.json: a dictionary with the correct transformation for each subject to align the data to the surface.

5. respdict.json: a dictionary with the number of TRs for each story in the stimulus set.
